<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/718336-why-do-the-characters-use-such-a-language">Why do the characters use such a language like &quot;thou, thee, art&quot;?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_718336'><a id="like_count_community_question_718336" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/718336?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">7 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F46170.For_Whom_the_Bell_Tolls">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/718336-why-do-the-characters-use-such-a-language">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/718336-why-do-the-characters-use-such-a-language">See all 12 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/59642909-elwood-bergman"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1473881685i/59642909._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/59642909-elwood-bergman">Elwood Bergman</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Spanish, as many other languages, has retained informal pronouns which we have lost in English. &quot;Thee&quot; and &quot;thou&quot; used to be informal words, only used<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Spanish, as many other languages, has retained informal pronouns which we have lost in English. "Thee" and "thou" used to be informal words, only used to address friends and younger people. It is our equivalent to tú, as opposed to usted. Part of what makes this great literature, I think, is that he gives a sense of how this culture can be both formal and familiar at the same time. Hemingway also does this in his use of heavily censored, but abundant expletives. It wouldn't have been the same if he wrote it any other way.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

<div class='flagAnswer'>
<a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link507316" title="Flag this answer as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=507316&amp;resource_type=CommunityAnswer&amp;return_url=%2Fquestions%2F718336-why-do-the-characters-use-such-a-language%2Fanswers%2F507316-spanish-as-many-other">flag</a>
</div>
<ul class='communityQAFooter answerFooter'>
</ul>

</div>
